What We've Learned Updated: The customer has custom reports that fetch data via SQL view from a database table. That database table contains data from AD about Active Directory Groups and their types. They were under impression that data is not coming up properly. ---------------------------------------
Saqib Sharif: I had a meeting with the customer today (20/02/2025). They wanted to create a job that would generate a report containing the following fields for user accounts in AD:

DomainName,
SamAccountName,
DisplayName,
DistinguishedName,
IsDeleted,
EmployeeId,
WhenCreated,
WhenChanged,
LastLogonTimestamp,
AccountExpires,
PwdLastSetDate,
ACCOUNTDISABLE,
OU
---------------------------------------------
Since OU is not readily available, we had to create a new SQL view. The data is now available for the customer.
---------------------------------------------

Steps for Resolution

  • Create a SQL View using the following command:

CREATE VIEW SA_ADInventory_UsersView_Custom AS

SELECT

  DomainName,

  SamAccountName,

  DisplayName,

  DistinguishedName,

  IsDeleted,

  EmployeeId,

  WhenCreated,

  WhenChanged,

  LastLogonTimestamp,

  AccountExpires,

  PwdLastSetDate,

  ACCOUNTDISABLE,

  REPLACE(SUBSTRING(DistinguishedName, CHARINDEX('OU=', DistinguishedName), LEN(DistinguishedName)), 'DN=', '') AS OU

FROM

  [StealthAudit].[dbo].[SA_ADInventory_UsersView];

 

  • Once the view is created, in Job Analysis Part, create another script with following data:

IF EXISTS (SELECT * FROM sys.views WHERE object_id = OBJECT_ID('SA_ADInventory_UsersView_Custom'))

BEGIN

  DROP VIEW SA_ADInventory_UsersView_Custom;

END

 

  • Create a report based on the data.

 

  • Rearrange the job tasks by setting the drop view to 1st, Create view to 2nd and create report to 3rd.
Steps to Reproduce Updated: There is no issue in the product. Steps to reproduce is irrelevant in this case.
